      <hedline>
        <hl1>Caring for the Elderly: A Precarious State</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alan G Rosenbloom letter comments on October 16 editorial urging better health care for elderly; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Health Coverage for the Elderly'' (editorial, Oct. 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Health Coverage for the Elderly'' (editorial, Oct. 16):</p>
        <p>America needs a health care delivery system that provides needed long-term care, social and supportive services as well as appropriate and affordable housing to serve the growing number of elderly people.</p>
        <p>The existing patchwork of programs is simply inadequate to serve the current need.</p>
        <p>Medicare currently covers only 11 percent of long-term nursing home care, with Medicaid and private resources covering most of the cost.</p>
        <p>Nursing home care will represent a diminishing amount of long-term care over all, with retirement communities, assisted living and home-  and community-based options becoming more attractive alternatives.</p>
        <p>All of us must look beyond Medicare to demand a national debate on nurturing a continuum of senior services that makes sense for the new millennium.</p>
        <p>ALAN G. ROSENBLOOM  Interim President  American Association of Homes  and Services for the Aging  Washington, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
